 in the context of white childrearing—and the cultivation of attitudes of white guilt, shame, and betrayal. To move beyond these distancing strategies, Sullivan argues, white people need a new ethos that acknowledges and transforms their whiteness in the pursuit of racial justice rather than seeking a self-righteous distance from it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAnti-racism -- United States. 0aAnti-racismzUnited States. 0aMiddle class -- United States. 0aMiddle classzUnited States. 0aUnited States -- Race relations. 0aUnited States -- Social conditions -- 1980-. 0aWhite peoplezUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aWhites -- United States -- Attitudes. 0aWhiteszUnited StatesxAttitudes. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPsychology : Psychology. 4aSociology : Social Change. 4aSociology : Sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2014z978311149015140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143845170140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438451701423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438451701/original  a978-3-11-149015-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles